{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658403"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:48:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:48:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20749"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20749"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.21,0.63,0.13,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13625"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97554"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13625","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13625"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20749"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80153"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"11717"},{"type":"tags","id":"12614"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32764"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32765"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97554"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPoliovirus causes a potentially devastating neurological disease that has been nearly eradicated through global vaccination efforts.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathogenesis of poliovirus infection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Formation of immune complexes in blood vessels","Direct cytolytic damage to peripheral nerves","Replication in motor neurones after systemic spread","Primary infection of respiratory epithelium","Autoimmune destruction of myelin sheaths"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Ereplication in motor neurones after systemic spread\u003C/strong\u003E. Poliovirus is an RNA virus of the enterovirus genus that enters the body via the faecal-oral route. It initially replicates in the mucosa of the pharynx and gut, including tonsils and Peyer patches in the ileum. The virus then spreads through lymphatics to lymph nodes and eventually enters the bloodstream, causing viraemia and fever. In approximately 1% of infections, the virus invades the central nervous system and replicates in motor neurones of the spinal cord (spinal poliomyelitis) or brainstem (bulbar poliomyelitis), causing the characteristic flaccid paralysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect cytolytic damage to peripheral nerves\u003C/strong\u003E - Poliovirus primarily affects motor neurones in the central nervous system (anterior horn cells of the spinal cord and brainstem), not peripheral nerves.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune destruction of myelin sheaths\u003C/strong\u003E - Poliovirus causes direct viral damage to neurones rather than triggering an autoimmune response against myelin. Demyelination is not a characteristic feature of poliomyelitis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary infection of respiratory epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E - While poliovirus can replicate in the pharyngeal mucosa, the primary site of entry and replication is the gastrointestinal tract, not the respiratory epithelium.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of immune complexes in blood vessels\u003C/strong\u003E - Poliomyelitis is not an immune complex-mediated disease. The pathology results from direct viral invasion and destruction of motor neurones.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPoliovirus binds to CD155 receptors on human cells, which are expressed on various cell types including epithelial cells, lymphocytes, and neurones. This binding facilitates viral entry and subsequent replication. The virus may reach the central nervous system either through the bloodstream or by retrograde axonal transport along motor neurones.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Poliovirus is an RNA virus of the enterovirus genus that is transmitted via the faecal-oral route.","Poliovirus binds to CD155 receptors on human cells and replicates in the pharyngeal and gut mucosa before potentially spreading to the central nervous system.","In approximately 1% of infections, poliovirus invades the central nervous system, causing paralysis by damaging motor neurones in the spinal cord or brainstem.","Most poliovirus infections are asymptomatic, with only a small percentage developing paralytic manifestations."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; page 351."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80153"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20749"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80153"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-07T21:53:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-07T21:56:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13625"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97554"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"met